des a Derridean supplément to exhausted, dominant genres (e.g. pastoral, lyric, epic), this study asks: what do these texts achieve by their supplementarity, and how do they achieve it?, and, the overarching question, why do these erudite poets turn to parody in an age of decline? Lindsay Kerr received her PhDin Spanish at Queen's University Belfast.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aParody in literature. 0aSpanish poetryyClassical period, 1500-1700xHistory and criticism. 4aEarly Modern Literature. 4aHispanic Studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / Spanish & Portuguese.2bisacsh  aHispanic.  aLatino.  aLatinx.  aanalysis.  aanthology.  agenre.  agreat britain.  aireland.  alanguage.  aliterature.  amedieval.  aparody.  apoetry.  aromance.  asixteenth century.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311143130740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781787440548?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781787440548423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781787440548/original  a978-3-11-143130-7  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles